Eduardo Motta de Moraes
on Sep 14, 2023

One issue that caught my attention is testing the delete and update endpoints, since they rely on datetime.now, whose value changes every time we call it. This means a test that passes today might fail in the future.

To overcome this and make the tests deterministic, I created a get_current_date function, which is then passed to the endpoints as a dependency using fastapi.Depends. 


from datetime import datetime as dt



def get_current_date() -> dt:

    return dt.today()



@app.delete("/tickets/{ticket_id}", response_model=None)

async def delete_ticket(

    ticket_id: int,

    db: Session = Depends(get_db),

    current_date: dt = Depends(get_current_date),

):

    try:

    ...

This dependency can then be overridden in the same way we did for get_db, so it will always return the same value for the "current date".


def override_get_current_date() -> dt:

    return dt(2022, 1, 1)



app.dependency_overrides[get_current_date] = override_get_current_date

To delete all the tickets if the event gets deleted I have tried 2 options:
1. Add line ```db.execute(delete(Ticket).where(Ticket.event_id == event_id))``` to operations.delete_event
2. Add ```tickets: Mapped[list[Ticket] = sqlalchemy.orm.relationship(cascade="all, delete")``` to Event model
Either worked.

REPLY
Arjan Egges
on Sep 12, 2023

Hi Rafal, thanks for posting both possible solutions. I have a personal preference for the first one. To me it's easier to understand what is happening since it's closer in structure to a SQL query. But YMMV.

REPLY
Arjan Egges
on Aug 31, 2023

Hi Juan, in order to retrieve a single ticket, you don't need the event id, because the ticket id should uniquely define the ticket that you want. So the endpoint would be @app.get("/tickets/{ticket_id}"). To get all the tickets from an event, the way you defined it works, but what you can also do is something like this: @app.get("/events/{event_id}) to get information about a particular event, and then the endpoint @app.get("/events/{event_id}/tickets) to get all the tickets for that event. That way, you don't introduce a new root-level route just for event tickets. Hope that helps!
